
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Effects of Gender on Arbitrators' Decisions
AU  - Bigoness, William J.
AU  - DuBose, Philip B.
Y1  - 1985/06/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256214
DO  - 10.5465/256214
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 485
EP  - 491
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses research pertaining to the effects of a grievant's gender on arbitration decisions in cases related to labor management relations. The study found that neither the arbitrators' rulings nor their perceptions of the seriousness of an offense were affected by a grievant's gender. Compared to male arbitrators, judgments rendered by women arbitrators were less severe. The offenses of female grievants were regarded as less serious. Results of the study failed to support the hypothesis that arbitrators of the same gender as grievants would treat these grievants favorably.
AB  - The article discusses research pertaining to the effects of a grievant's gender on arbitration decisions in cases related to labor management relations. The study found that neither the arbitrators' rulings nor their perceptions of the seriousness of an offense were affected by a grievant's gender. Compared to male arbitrators, judgments rendered by women arbitrators were less severe. The offenses of female grievants were regarded as less serious. Results of the study failed to support the hypothesis that arbitrators of the same gender as grievants would treat these grievants favorably.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256214
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256214
