TY  - JOUR
T1  - Outcomes of Role Stress: A Multisample Constructive Replication
AU  - Kemery, Edward R.
AU  - Bedeian, Arthur G.
AU  - Mossholder, Kevin W.
AU  - Touliatos, John
Y1  - 1985/06/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256206
DO  - 10.5465/256206
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 363
EP  - 375
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Responses from four separate samples of accountants and hospital employees provided a constructive replication of the Bedeian and Armenakis (1981) model of the causal nexus between role stress and selected outcome variables. We investigated the relationship between both role ambiguity and role conflict ? as specific forms of rote stress ? and job-related tension, job satisfaction, and propensity to leave, using LISREL IV, a technique capable of providing statistical data for a hypothesized population model, as well as for specific causal paths. Results, which support the Bedeian and Armenakis model, are discussed in light of previous research.
AB  - Responses from four separate samples of accountants and hospital employees provided a constructive replication of the Bedeian and Armenakis (1981) model of the causal nexus between role stress and selected outcome variables. We investigated the relationship between both role ambiguity and role conflict ? as specific forms of rote stress ? and job-related tension, job satisfaction, and propensity to leave, using LISREL IV, a technique capable of providing statistical data for a hypothesized population model, as well as for specific causal paths. Results, which support the Bedeian and Armenakis model, are discussed in light of previous research.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256206
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256206
Y2  - 2026/04/24
