T1  - Reactions to Feedback: The Role of Attributions
AU  - Liden, Robert C.
AU  - Mitchell, Terence R.
Y1  - 1985/06/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256202
DO  - 10.5465/256202
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 291
EP  - 308
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study tested reactions to feedback in an experimental simulation. Feedback specificity and information that could be used to make causal inferences were manipulated through varying information on consistency, distinctiveness, and consensus. As predicted, subjects rated specific feedback more positively than they rated nonspecific feedback, and preferred feedback that suggested an external cause of poor performance to feedback that suggested an internal cause. However, the latter was not preferred to nonspecific feedback.
AB  - This study tested reactions to feedback in an experimental simulation. Feedback specificity and information that could be used to make causal inferences were manipulated through varying information on consistency, distinctiveness, and consensus. As predicted, subjects rated specific feedback more positively than they rated nonspecific feedback, and preferred feedback that suggested an external cause of poor performance to feedback that suggested an internal cause. However, the latter was not preferred to nonspecific feedback.
