T1  - An Empirical Examination of the Relationship between Corporate Social Responsibility and Profitability
AU  - Aupperle, Kenneth E.
AU  - Carroll, Archie B.
AU  - Hatfield, John D.
Y1  - 1985/06/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256210
DO  - 10.5465/256210
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 446
EP  - 463
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Although there has been considerable research into the relationship between corporate social responsibility and profitability, it has frequently reflected either an ideological bias or limited methodological procedures. Research has also been impeded by the difficulty of adequately measuring corporate social responsibility. This study, using an elaborate, forced-choice instrument administered to corporate CEOs, did not find any relationship between social responsibility and profitability. Specifically, varying levels of social orientation were not found to correlate with performance differences.
AB  - Although there has been considerable research into the relationship between corporate social responsibility and profitability, it has frequently reflected either an ideological bias or limited methodological procedures. Research has also been impeded by the difficulty of adequately measuring corporate social responsibility. This study, using an elaborate, forced-choice instrument administered to corporate CEOs, did not find any relationship between social responsibility and profitability. Specifically, varying levels of social orientation were not found to correlate with performance differences.
