TY  - JOUR
T1  - Vertical Integration and Corporate Strategy
AU  - Harrigan, Kathryn Rudie
Y1  - 1985/06/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256208
DO  - 10.5465/256208
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 397
EP  - 425
VL  - 28
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Proposing a new look at vertical integration and the dimensions that comprise it, this study develops a framework for predicting when firms use make-or-buy decisions. The strategic business units (SBUs) studied made fewer products and services in-house and firms were engaged in fewer stages of processing when demand was highly uncertain than they did when demand was more certain. Internal transfers from upstream or to downstream business units were more numerous when synergies with adjacent SBUs were substantial than when they were not. Some competitive imitation of vertical integration strategies occurred, and firms with high market shares sought higher ownership stakes in stages of processing adjacent to those markets.
AB  - Proposing a new look at vertical integration and the dimensions that comprise it, this study develops a framework for predicting when firms use make-or-buy decisions. The strategic business units (SBUs) studied made fewer products and services in-house and firms were engaged in fewer stages of processing when demand was highly uncertain than they did when demand was more certain. Internal transfers from upstream or to downstream business units were more numerous when synergies with adjacent SBUs were substantial than when they were not. Some competitive imitation of vertical integration strategies occurred, and firms with high market shares sought higher ownership stakes in stages of processing adjacent to those markets.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256208
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256208
Y2  - 2026/04/24
